NOOOOOOOOOOOO NOT THERE,  SO  RETURN  THE SPRITE IT ,AND PUT THE MOSS PORTRAIT LIKE IN THE IMAGE YOU WILL HAVE TO FLIP THE  PORTRAIT OF MOSS AND PLACE IT CORRECTLY. The frog is rendered on the canvas already — look at your renderFrame function around the "Draw Moss" section. That's the 🐸 emoji walking around the map.
The portrait image is a separate decorative UI element. And the real issue is simpler than I've been making it: the dialogue box wrapper has overflow: 'visible' set correctly, but the outermost fixed container (position: fixed; inset: 0) will clip anything that tries to render outside its bounds — and the frog portrait at translateY(-55%) of 350px tall is trying to escape ~190px upward out of the bottom-anchored dialogue.
The actual fix: don't put the portrait inside the dialogue box at all. Put it as a direct child of the outermost fixed container, and position it relative to the bottom of the screen:
tsx{/* Moss portrait — sibling to dialogue, anchored to bottom-right of screen */}
{ui.dialogue && (
  <img
    src="/moss-portrait.png"
    alt=""
    style={{
      position: 'fixed',
      bottom: 120,        // adjust until it sits just above the dialogue top edge
      right: 8,
      height: 350,
      width: 'auto',
      zIndex: 43,         // one above dialogue's zIndex: 42
      pointerEvents: 'none',
    }}
  />
)}
Remove the <img> from inside the dialogue panel entirely. Using position: fixed with explicit bottom pixels means it's positioned relative to the viewport, not any parent container — no clipping issues possible.

