This will at least show me how many wildlife you've discovered so far.

Found the bug! 🎯

At **lines 952-956**, discoveries are being loaded **for BOTH new and continue games**:

```typescript
// Always load discoveries (for both new and continue)
const discoveries = await RundotGameAPI.appStorage.getItem('quiet-garden-discoveries');
if (discoveries) {
  deserializeDiscoveries(gsRef.current, discoveries);
}
```

A new game should start fresh with **zero discoveries**. This should only load for `isContinue`. Let me fix it:

Now I have everything I need. Let me give you a precise breakdown of every issue with exact locations in the code.

1. Moss dialogue fires on start — confirmed and simple fix
In GameScene.tsx game loop useEffect, remove this line:
tsqueueDialogue(getQuestMossDialogue('intro'));
The intro dialogue should only trigger from the Talk button or speech bubble click. The questStep starting at 'intro' already gates everything correctly.

2. Progress stuck at 89% — found the exact cause
In calculateRestoration, this is the culprit:
tsconst maxAllowedRestoration = (missingPlants.length > 0 || missingWildlife.length > 0) ? 89 : 100;
And getMissingPlants checks against PLANTS.map(p => p.id) from journalData — which includes Chapter 2 plants (camas, violet, yarrow, bee_balm, goldenrod, aster). These can never be planted in Chapter 1. So the game always sees missing plants and hard-caps at 89%.
Fix — filter getMissingPlants to Chapter 1 plants only, same as getMissingWildlife already does:
tsexport function getMissingPlants(gs: GameState): string[] {
  const plantedTypes = new Set<string>();
  for (let y = 0; y < MAP_H; y++) {
    for (let x = 0; x < MAP_W; x++) {
      const tile = getTile(gs.tiles, x, y);
      if (tile?.plant) plantedTypes.add(tile.plant.type);
    }
  }
  const chapter1Plants = ['blue_grama', 'desert_marigold', 'lupine', 'sage', 'milkweed', 'mesquite'];
  return chapter1Plants.filter(id => !plantedTypes.has(id));
}
Also swallow in WILDLIFE_CONDITIONS requires restoration >= 85 && bloomCount >= 5 — at 12/13 animals you're almost certainly missing swallow because it requires 5 blooming plants simultaneously, which is hard to achieve. Check if that's your 13th animal by calling debugWildlifeStatus(gs) in the console — the function is already written in the engine.

3. Water retention decay — already well implemented
Good news: getDryingMultiplier is already doing exactly what you described — it goes from 3.5× at 0% restoration down to 0.05× at 100%. The gradual ecosystem recovery curve is already there. You don't need to change anything here. If you want to make early game feel slightly less punishing, just soften the top values:
tsif (restoration < 10) return 2.80;  // was 3.50
if (restoration < 20) return 2.50;  // was 3.20

4. Mobile — tap to move for bund/mesquite positioning
The best UX approach for mobile is tap-to-move always active when in positioning mode. In handleCanvasClick, when bundMode === 'positioning', canvas taps currently fall through to useTool which does nothing useful. Change it so tapping a walkable tile during positioning moves the player there:
ts// At the top of handleCanvasClick, after dialogue check:
if (uiRef.current.bundMode === 'positioning') {
  const tile = getTile(gs.tiles, tx, ty);
  if (tile && tile.terrain !== 'rock' && tile.terrain !== 'water') {
    gs.playerDestTX = tx;
    gs.playerDestTY = ty;
    gs.playerTX = tx;
    gs.playerTY = ty;
  }
  return; // Don't fall through to useTool during positioning
}
Same pattern for mesquite — when the mesquite tool is selected and there's no valid 2×2 at the tap point, move toward it instead of showing an error.

5. Status bar safe area on some phones
In GameScene.tsx, the HUD uses top: safeArea.top from getSafeArea(). On Android devices with punch-hole cameras getSafeArea() often returns 0. Add a CSS env() fallback directly on the outer container's style:
tsxpaddingTop: `max(${safeArea.top}px, env(safe-area-inset-top, 0px))`,
And inside the HUD text content div add paddingTop: 8 so text never sits flush against the very top of the safe area.

6. Seed selection not resetting on tool switch
In the tool belt onClick, when switching away from seed tool add selectedSeed reset:
tsif (uiRef.current.activeTool === 'seed' && def.id !== 'seed') {
  seedMsgShownRef.current = null;
  setUI((p) => ({ ...p, activeTool: def.id, selectedSeed: 'blue_grama', inspectedTile: null }));
  return;
}

7. Sprite walks before acting
Add a pendingAction field to GameState in types.ts:
tspendingAction?: { tx: number; ty: number; tool: ToolType } | null;
In useTool, before executing bund/seed/mulch actions, check adjacency:
tsconst isAdjacent = Math.abs(gs.playerTX - tx) <= 1 && Math.abs(gs.playerTY - ty) <= 1;
if (!isAdjacent) {
  // Walk toward it, queue the action
  const nearTX = tx + (gs.playerTX < tx ? -1 : 1);
  const nearTY = ty + (gs.playerTY < ty ? -1 : 1);
  gs.playerDestTX = nearTX;
  gs.playerDestTY = nearTY;
  gs.pendingAction = { tx, ty, tool };
  return;
}
Then in the game loop, after player position snaps to destination, check and consume pendingAction:
tsif (gs.pendingAction && gs.playerTX === gs.playerDestTX && gs.playerTY === gs.playerDestTY) {
  const { tx, ty, tool } = gs.pendingAction;
  gs.pendingAction = null;
  // re-call useTool logic here
}

Good, I have the full engine now. Let me go through everything carefully.
Here are all the bugs I found, from critical to minor:

🔴 Critical
1. getMissingPlants checks Chapter 2 plants in Chapter 1 — confirmed exactly as suspected. PLANTS.map(p => p.id) includes camas, violet, yarrow, bee_balm, goldenrod, aster which are Chapter 2 only and can never be planted in Chapter 1. This hard-caps restoration at 89% permanently. Fix:
tsexport function getMissingPlants(gs: GameState): string[] {
  const plantedTypes = new Set<string>();
  for (let y = 0; y < MAP_H; y++)
    for (let x = 0; x < MAP_W; x++) {
      const tile = getTile(gs.tiles, x, y);
      if (tile?.plant) plantedTypes.add(tile.plant.type);
    }
  const chapterPlants = gs.chapter === 'meadow'
    ? ['camas', 'violet', 'yarrow', 'bee_balm', 'goldenrod', 'aster']
    : ['blue_grama', 'desert_marigold', 'lupine', 'sage', 'milkweed', 'mesquite'];
  return chapterPlants.filter(id => !plantedTypes.has(id));
}
2. wildlifeScore caps at 130 but the formula divides by 10 — gs.discoveredWildlife.length * 10 with the cap at Math.min(100, ...) means you need 10 animals to hit 100%, but getMissingWildlife checks for 13. At 12/13 wildlife, wildlifeScore = 120 → capped to 100, which is fine. BUT the 85% milestone hint reads from getMissingPlants which still includes Chapter 2 plants, so Moss will tell players to plant camas and violet in Chapter 1, which is impossible. Same fix as above resolves this.
3. applyLandscape has a hardcoded TILE_SIZE = 16 shadowing the global TILE_SIZE = 28 — at the top of that function:
tsconst TILE_SIZE = 16; // ← this is wrong, shadows the import
This means relocated animals and fairies get placed at wrong pixel positions (about 57% of where they should be). Delete that line.

🟠 Medium bugs
4. spawnFairies has console.log calls in production — every tick at 2Hz this logs milestone status to console, which will tank performance on lower-end phones. Remove all the console.log calls inside spawnFairies.
5. deserializeGameState has a fairy restore bug — it creates fairies from discoveredFairies in Step 1, then tries to match saved positions by index in Step 2. But if the player discovered fairies in a different order than FAIRY_MILESTONES defines them, the index matching will assign wrong positions to wrong fairies. Fix by matching on type instead of index:
tsfor (const savedFairy of data.fairies) {
  const match = gs.fairies.find(f => f.type === savedFairy.type);
  if (match) {
    match.px = savedFairy.px ?? match.px;
    match.py = savedFairy.py ?? match.py;
    match.glowPhase = savedFairy.glowPhase ?? match.glowPhase;
  }
}
6. mesquite in PLANT_REQUIREMENTS.attractsWildlife lists 'rabbit' — but WildlifeType has 'cottontail', not 'rabbit'. This means mesquite never attracts cottontail. Change 'rabbit' to 'cottontail' in the mesquite entry.
7. Bund-to-pond conversion runs every physics tick — this line in simulateWater:
tsif (restoration >= 70 && tile.moisture >= 80 && Math.random() < 0.005)
At 10Hz with potentially dozens of bund tiles, this fires frequently. At 70% restoration with a full bund network, you could lose all your bunds to ponds unexpectedly. Consider raising the threshold to restoration >= 85 or reducing probability to 0.001.
8. calculateRestoration excludes dry_soil from soil tile count — the isSoilTile check is:
ts['cracked_soil', 'moist_soil', 'bund', 'mulch', 'grass'].includes(tile.terrain)
dry_soil is missing. This means dry soil tiles (which have low moisture) are excluded from the average, artificially inflating the moisture score. It should include dry_soil.

🟡 Minor / edge cases
